### **1\. Executive Summary**

In an increasingly volatile global economy, the ability to understand and anticipate market dynamics is paramount for effective policymaking and strategic investment. Traditional economic analysis, however, relies on lagging indicators derived from official statistics published with significant delay, offering a retrospective view of a past reality. This project confronts this critical latency problem by proposing the creation of the **Economic Observatory**, a comprehensive, near-real-time big data solution designed to transform high-velocity administrative data into forward-looking, actionable intelligence.

Our project addresses the core challenge that key stakeholders lack the tools to analyze the complex dynamics of business entry, growth, and exit at the speed at which they occur. To close this gap, we will design and implement a comprehensive, end-to-end data pipeline that integrates the core concepts of the IADD, BEAD, and ARTS courses into a unified, cohesive system. The platform will be architected as a modern, containerized service founded on the principles of the Data Lakehouse.

We will ingest a continuous stream of business registration data from [data.gov.sg](https://data.gov.sg), enriched with macroeconomic indicators and geospatial property data for contextual analysis. At the heart of the system is **PySpark**, which serves as the primary engine for distributed batch and real-time data processing. We augment PySpark with **dbt (data build tool)** to deliver modular, testable, and maintainable analytics workflows.

All data will be stored in **Delta Lake format** on a **MinIO (S3-compatible)** object store, supporting ACID transactions, schema enforcement, and time-travel for reproducible analysis. This Lakehouse architecture ensures the integrity and flexibility required for both historical and real-time analytics.

To move beyond descriptive analysis, the platform will feature a predictive analytics layer powered by Python-native tools:

* A **Survival Analysis model** built using `PySpark MLlib`’s `AFTSurvivalRegression`, to estimate the likelihood of firm survival over time.

* An **NLP classification pipeline** using `Spark NLP for Python`, to automatically categorize businesses by industry based on textual attributes.

* A **real-time anomaly detection engine** using **PySpark Structured Streaming**, to flag unusual spikes in registrations or cessations as they occur.

The final deliverable will be a fully reproducible system encapsulated in a single Git repository, featuring a **one-command Kubernetes deployment**, a detailed final report, and an **interactive Streamlit dashboard** for data exploration and stakeholder decision support. Through this project, we demonstrate mastery of modern data engineering techniques using PySpark and the broader Python ecosystem, while delivering a practical tool for high-frequency economic analysis in the Singaporean context.

### **2\. Literature Review and Problem Statement**

**Problem Statement:** Economic policymakers, investors, and corporate strategists currently rely on low-frequency, retrospective data (e.g., quarterly GDP, annual reports) to assess economic health. This inherent latency creates a significant blind spot, hindering their ability to react swiftly to emerging trends, market shocks, and structural shifts. The fundamental problem is the absence of a platform capable of ingesting, processing, and analyzing high-velocity, granular data on business dynamics in a timely, predictive, and integrated manner. This project aims to build such a platform, providing a unified, near-real-time view of historical trends, geospatial business concentrations, and predictive insights into firm survival, thereby enabling a paradigm shift from reactive to proactive economic analysis.

**Literature Review:**

Our project is situated at the intersection of economic theory, data science, and big data engineering. The intellectual framework is built upon three pillars:

1. **Firm Demography and Economic Dynamism:** The study of business dynamics is a cornerstone of modern economics, most famously framed by Joseph Schumpeter's (1934) theory of "creative destruction," which posits that long-term economic growth is driven by the continuous cycle of firm entry, innovation, and exit. Subsequent research has consistently shown that firm-level characteristics such as age, size, and industry are powerful predictors of survival (Audretsch, 1991). Methodologically, Survival Analysis has emerged as the superior technique for modeling these phenomena. Unlike traditional regression models, it correctly handles time-to-event data and accounts for right-censored observations (i.e., firms that have not yet failed), providing a more accurate and nuanced understanding of survival probabilities (Box-Steffensmeier & Jones, 2004; Cleves et al., 2010).  
2. **The Value of Data Enrichment in Economic Analysis:** Modern economic research increasingly emphasizes the value of enriching traditional administrative data with alternative data sources. The field of economic geography, pioneered by scholars like Michael Porter (1998), establishes that location and the clustering of businesses are critical variables that influence productivity and innovation. Concurrently, the "text as data" paradigm has demonstrated the power of using Natural Language Processing (NLP) to extract strategic information from unstructured text. Techniques for classifying firms based on their descriptions or extracting sentiment from reports provide powerful, non-financial indicators of performance and strategy (Gentzkow, Kelly, & Taddy, 2019). Our project will integrate both geospatial and NLP-derived features to create a richer, more predictive dataset.  
3. **Big Data Architectures for High-Frequency Analysis:** The volume, velocity, and variety of modern data streams render traditional data processing architectures insufficient. The **Lambda Architecture** (Marz & Warren, 2015\) provided a foundational pattern for combining batch and real-time processing to handle this challenge. More recently, the **Data Lakehouse** paradigm has emerged, combining the scalability and low cost of data lakes with the data management features of data warehouses. This is achieved through transactional table formats like **Delta Lake** or **Apache Iceberg**, which provide ACID compliance and schema enforcement over data stored in open file formats (e.g., Parquet) on cloud object storage. These architectures, powered by distributed computing engines like **Apache Spark**, enable scalable analytics on massive datasets.

**Identified Research Gap:** Our review of the literature identifies a clear and compelling research gap: the lack of an **integrated platform that applies a modern, real-time data engineering paradigm to the domain of firm demography.** While the theories of economic dynamics are well-established, their empirical validation has been constrained by the low frequency of available data. This project will be among the first to build a unified system that combines real-time data ingestion, a Data Lakehouse architecture, geospatial analysis, NLP enrichment, and predictive survival modeling. Its core contribution is to enable the measurement and analysis of "creative destruction" not in years or quarters, but in near-real-time, unlocking a new frontier of high-frequency economic observation.

### **3\. Technical Architecture**

Our architecture is designed as a modern, containerized service that adheres to all mandatory and desirable project requirements.1 It is founded on the principles of a multi-layered Data Lakehouse, ensuring scalability, reliability, and a clean separation of concerns between data processing and analytics engineering. The entire system will be reproducible via Kubernetes manifests for one-command deployment.

#### **3.2. Technology Stack and Justification**

| Stage | Component | Technology Choice | Justification |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **A. Ingestion** | Streaming Platform | **Apache Kafka** | Provides a fault-tolerant, high-throughput, and scalable message bus for real-time data streams. While modern alternatives like Redpanda offer performance benefits 3, Kafka's vast ecosystem and status as the de facto industry standard make it the most robust and strategically sound choice for a project emphasizing integration and mastery of a broad toolset.1 |
| **B. Storage** | Object Store | **MinIO** | An S3-compatible object store that serves as the scalable and cost-effective foundation for our Data Lakehouse. Its suitability for local development, as recommended in the guidelines, makes it ideal for this project.1 |
|  | Table Format | **Delta Lake** | The recommended transactional table format, offering ACID transactions, time travel, and schema enforcement over the data lake.1 Given that Spark is the mandatory processing engine, Delta Lake's native integration and performance optimizations within the Spark ecosystem make it the superior choice over alternatives like Apache Iceberg for this project.8 |
| **C. Processing** | Core ETL Engine | **Apache Spark** | The mandatory engine for all large-scale ingestion, ETL, streaming, and analytics.1 Its distributed, in-memory processing capabilities are essential for handling the scale of the business registration dataset. |
|  | Analytics Engineering | **dbt (data build tool)** | Explicitly welcomed in the project guidelines 1, dbt will be used to transform data from the Silver to the Gold layer. It brings software engineering best practices (modularity, testing, version control, documentation) to analytics, elevating the project's quality and maintainability.14  |
| **D. Analytics** | Machine Learning | **Spark MLlib & MLflow** | We will use MLlib's AFTSurvivalRegression for survival prediction 23 and MLflow to manage the complete MLOps lifecycle, from experiment tracking to model deployment. This demonstrates a professional approach to machine learning development.1 |
|  | NLP | **Spark NLP** | A state-of-the-art library for NLP on Spark. It will be used to build a robust pipeline for industry classification, providing a critical feature for our analysis and demonstrating advanced data enrichment capabilities.28 |
| **E. Visualization** | Dashboard | **Streamlit** | A powerful, Python-native framework for building and deploying custom interactive web applications. It allows for the rapid development of a rich, data-driven dashboard to visualize our findings, fulfilling a key (though optional) project criterion.1 |
| **Orchestration** | Containerization | **Docker & Kubernetes** | The entire pipeline will be containerized using Docker and made reproducible via Kubernetes manifests, as required.1 This ensures a one-command setup and demonstrates a mastery of modern deployment practices. |

### **4\. Dataset Analysis**

Our project will be built upon a foundation of publicly available data from Singaporean government agencies, ensuring compliance with open data licenses and providing a rich source for analysis.

* **Primary Dataset (ACRA):** Our primary dataset is the **"Entities Registered with ACRA"**. We will employ a hybrid ingestion strategy for this source: an initial **batch load** using the complete static `.csv` file to establish the historical baseline of over 1.6 million records, followed by **periodic API calls** to the `data.gov.sg` DataStore API to fetch incremental daily or weekly updates. This approach provides a complete historical context while ensuring the data remains current. [Entities Registered with ACRA | ACRA | data.gov.sg](https://data.gov.sg/datasets/d_3f960c10fed6145404ca7b821f263b87/view)  
* **Macroeconomic Enrichment (SingStat):** The base data will be enriched with key macroeconomic time-series from the SingStat API. This is joined to the ACRA data using the `uen_issue_date` to align each firm with the economic conditions prevalent during its lifecycle. We will specifically target tables such as **'Gross Domestic Product By Industry' (ID: M015731)**, **'Consumer Price Index' (ID: M213901)**, and crucial business dynamics data like **'Formation Of All Business Entities By Industry' (ID: M085641)** and **'Cessation Of All Business Entities By Industry' (ID: M085651)**. [(DOS) | SingStat Table Builder – Developer API](https://tablebuilder.singstat.gov.sg/view-api/for-developers)  
* **Geospatial Enrichment (URA):** For geospatial context, we will leverage the URA's token-based API to retrieve residential property rental data (specifically the **`PMI_Resi_Rental_Median`** service) as a robust proxy for commercial property trends. This data will be joined to the ACRA dataset by mapping each business's `reg_postal_code` to a postal district and aligning it with the quarterly `refPeriod` from the URA data. [Private Non-Landed Residential Properties Median Rentals by Name – API Reference](https://eservice.ura.gov.sg/maps/api/#private-residential-property)  
* **More would be needed along the way.**

| Vetting Checklist | Analysis |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Problem-Fit** | **Yes.** The dataset provides the necessary firm-level attributes (registration date, cessation date, legal type, address) to analyze business dynamics, model geospatial clustering, and predict firm survival, directly addressing our problem statement. |
| **Ingestion Path** | **Hybrid.** The primary ACRA dataset will be ingested using a two-stage process: an initial bulk load of the historical `.csv` file, followed by daily scheduled jobs calling the DataStore API for incremental updates. Enrichment data from SingStat and URA will be fetched exclusively via their respective APIs. |
| **Format & Quality** | **Good.** The data is available in standard CSV and JSON formats. While it will require cleansing and standardization, it is well-structured and highly parsable. |
| **Scale** | **Sufficient.** The dataset contains millions of records spanning several decades, justifying a distributed, Spark-based solution. |
| **Licensing** | **Permissive.** All chosen datasets are provided under the Singapore Open Data Licence, permitting use for academic projects. |

### **5\. Scope of Work and Effort Estimate**

The project will be executed over 12 weeks, with the work distributed across four distinct phases. The total estimated effort is 60 person-days, assuming a five-person team with each member contributing the required 12 days of effort.1 This scope includes the implementation of advanced analytics through

**machine learning** (survival prediction), **NLP** (industry classification), and **real-time streaming analytics** (anomaly detection), thereby fulfilling the desirable criteria for an exemplary project.1

| Phase | Task | Sub-Tasks | Estimated Person-Days |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **A: Setup & Ingestion (Weeks 1-3)** | **Infrastructure & Data Sourcing** | \- Provision Kubernetes environment (Podman Desktop).   \- Set up MinIO buckets, users, and access policies.  \- Deploy and configure a 3-node Kafka cluster.  \- Develop and test Python producers to fetch data from data.gov.sg, SingStat, and URA APIs and publish to Kafka topics. | **12** |
| **B: Lakehouse & ETL Pipeline (Weeks 4-6)** | **Core Data Pipeline Construction** | \- Develop initial Spark Structured Streaming jobs to ingest from Kafka into Bronze Delta tables (raw, immutable).  \- Develop Spark batch/streaming jobs for Bronze-to-Silver transformations (cleansing, data type casting, schema enforcement).  \- Set up dbt project, configure profiles.yml to connect to Spark Thrift server.  \- Develop dbt models to create Gold layer tables (e.g., dim\_business, dim\_location, fct\_registrations).  \- Implement data quality tests in dbt for key Gold tables. | **15** |
| **C: ML Modeling & NLP (Weeks 7-9)** | **Advanced Analytics Implementation** | \- Perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) on Silver/Gold tables to identify features for ML. \- Develop the Spark NLP pipeline for industry classification and apply it to generate the industry feature. \- Engineer feature vectors for the survival model.  \- Train, tune, and evaluate the AFTSurvivalRegression model using MLflow for experiment tracking.  \- Develop the Spark Structured Streaming job for real-time anomaly detection. | **18** |
| **D: Serving, Finalization & Reporting (Weeks 10-12)** | **Visualization & Project Delivery** | \- Develop an interactive dashboard using Streamlit to visualize key trends and anomalies.  \- Create a simple Flask/FastAPI wrapper around the trained survival model to serve predictions.  \- Integrate the prediction API with the Streamlit dashboard.  \- Author the comprehensive final report and installation guide. \- Prepare and rehearse the final project demonstration. | **15** |
| **Total** |  |  | **60** |
